1. outline

1996 Atlanta Olympic Games - Official Film

From July 19, 1996 to August 4, 1996 in the United States The 26th Summer Olympics held in Atlanta .

It is an Olympic Games that marks the 100th anniversary of the birth of the modern Olympics and shows the peak of Olympic commercialization. In the end, this competition caused the IOC to look at the United States unfavorably, and it is a competition that can never be considered a success.

Japan in 1990 The venue was selected at the IOC General Assembly held in Tokyo , and there was a lot of controversy from the time the venue was selected. As it is the 100th anniversary of the modern Olympics, Greece , the first host of the modern Olympics, inherits the Olympic spirit advocated by Baron Pierre de Coubertin. There was nothing more certain than the justification for holding the Olympics again in Athens . Therefore, the world agreed that Athens was the appropriate place to host the 1996 Games, and everyone naturally expected Athens to be selected. However, the results were overturned in the last 4 rounds of voting, and eventually the final selection was made in Atlanta, not Athens. People were taken aback by this unexpected decision, and the backlash from the Greek government was particularly strong.

There is also a theory in the world that the 1992 Winter Olympics and the 1994 Winter Olympics were ultimately held on the North American continent rather than Europe due to concerns that it would go against the continental rotation theory since both were held in Europe. However, it seemed more reasonable to point out that granting the right to host the Summer Olympics for the first time in 12 years to the United States , which had already hosted the Summer Olympics in Los Angeles in 1984, was giving too much support to certain countries. For reference, the 1992 Winter Olympics were held in Albertville, France , the Summer Olympics were held in Barcelona, Spain , and the 1994 Winter Olympics were held in Lillehammer, Norway . [3]

The most compelling reason for this decision is the lobby of American companies. In particular, there was a lobby of Coca-Cola , the main sponsor of the IOC, based in Atlanta, and the votes of some IOC members bought in the process. This became known to the world as it was exposed along with the incident in which IOC members were bribed by Salt Lake City at the time of the 2002 Salt Lake City Winter Olympics . Naturally, it caused great controversy, and eventually several members of the IOC resigned for violating their ethical obligations.

When there was opposition to the selection of the venue, the IOC's explanation was that Atlanta was intended to honor the feat of Rev. Martin Luther King, his hometown. Still, Athens hosted the 2004 Athens Olympics eight years later, and although it is said that it was compensated a little for this failure, in Greece, which has been struggling with wage cuts and youth unemployment since the 2010s, the Olympics were held in 1996 instead of 2004 . It is said that if it had been, it would not have suffered because of the damn euro. [4]

3. event

4. failed olympics

On July 27, during the Games, a bombing occurred at the Olympic Park, killing two people and injuring 111 people. In addition , Richard Jewell, who was serving as a temporary event security guard at the time, [5] was a hero who reduced casualties by evacuating citizens by discovering explosives in advance, but three days later, suspicions of a self-made act were raised in the media and he was accused of being a terrorist. For months after the charges were cleared in October 1996, many law enforcement officials privately claimed that Richard Jewell was involved in the bombings, despite the lack of evidence and information that Jewell was not involved. Although he was never formally charged, before the charges were released, the FBI conducted two thorough searches of his home, interrogated his co-workers, investigated Jewel's background, and kept him under 24-hour surveillance, and at the time people considered the notorious terrorist Unabomber and idiot . It was mocked as 'Unadoofus', a combination of 'doofus'. The pressure was only eased after Jewel's lawyers hired a former FBI agent to manage the lie detector. Jewel passed the lie detector test. It wasn't until 2003 that the real culprit, Eric Rudolph , was arrested and he was sentenced to life in prison in 2005. Afterwards, Jewel won against NBC and the New York Times, who had framed him, but the lawsuit against Cox Communications, the publisher of the Atlanta Journal, was filed in 2011, four years after his death. He lost. In his later years he became a police officer and gave lectures before passing away on August 29, 2007.( # ) [6]

1980 The Winter Olympics were held in Lake Placid , and the Summer Olympics were held in Los Angeles in 1984. Isn't the United States overindulging in the Olympics due to the fact that the Summer Olympics are being held again only 12 years later? There were also concerns. Later, in 2002, six years later in the United States Salt Lake also hosted the Winter Olympics . [7]

As the competition flowed so commercially, there was skepticism about whether the Olympics should be like this. It was not good to see that all parts were paid, and even volunteers were active with sponsor logos. The so-called 'Olympic Zone', including the area around the Olympic stadium, athlete's village/reporter's village, and media center, was a profiteering market for Olympic sponsor companies, and even payment was possible only with the sponsor 's credit card . The media center was also placed too commercially, and the order of matches was the same. In addition, the conflict between NBC and the IOC , the main broadcasting company on the US side, was also discussed. In 1992, troubled commercialism in Barcelona culminated in Atlanta.

This serious condition can be seen just by looking at the opening ceremony. NBC, the US host broadcaster, not just broadcasting, showed advertisements during the opening ceremony, and even had a short break in the middle of the Olympic opening ceremony for these advertisements. Even if a 30-second advertisement is shown, it feels long at such an opening ceremony, but four minutes were devoted to the advertisement. It was the closing ceremony that showed this feeling comprehensively, but there were many negative opinions that it was more like a famous singer's closing ceremony than an Olympic closing performance. American singers such as Gloria Estefan , Little Richard , and Stevie Wonder, as well as great artists such as BB King and Al Green , all mobilized, but the planning itself is said to have the feel of a Las Vegas-style show unique to the United States.

The amateur spirit advocated by Baron Coubertin has completely disappeared and has been reduced to a thorough marketing tool for multinational corporations . Six years later, at the 2002 Salt Lake City Winter Olympics, the United States' image in the Olympics was completely tarnished as the United States used the Olympics strategically in relation to the 9/11 attacks. In addition, the bribery scandal in the United States during the Salt Lake Olympics bid was exposed. As the fetishism of the Atlanta Olympics and the excessive patriotism of the Salt Lake Olympics coincided, antipathy to the United States grew stronger even within the IOC , and despite the maximum commercial benefit possible, the 2012 New York Department 2016 Chicago 's bid to host the Olympics ended in early elimination. Eventually, after decades, the 2028 Olympics will be held again in Los Angeles.

Until the end of the tournament, the evaluation of the Atlanta Olympics was not good. Finally, in his closing speech, IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch did not say the customary 'The Best Olympics Ever', but simply said, Well Done, Atlanta. This is the first and last competition ever to hear such words.

As a side note, the competition is crazy, but the mascot is Izzy. [8] As expected, the majority of reviews say that it is a dead end. It was said to embody an imaginary alien creature, but its shape was so strange that children cried when they saw this life-size mascot, so it only appeared once at the opening ceremony and was kicked out of the closing ceremony. Even Atlanta citizens and nearby residents said, "Because it's Atlanta, wouldn't there be something like 'Smiling Peanuts ', a specialty of the area?" It is said that complaints poured in when such a strange mascot appeared. It kind of reminds me of this guy . On the other hand, the Paralympic mascot Blaze , a character modeled after Atlanta's symbol, the Phoenix , was so well-received that some residents still wear it on their car license plates.

6. characteristic

Canada 's Donovan Bailey set a new men's 100m world record.

Michael Johnson of the United States gained great popularity with his unique golden spikes and unique running technique, winning the 200m and 400m at the same time and monopolizing the honor of being the world's best sprinter, which the original 100m winner always enjoyed. Johnson's time of 19.32 at the time was evaluated as a great record that was not paid for. [11] , The American press used to publish the title of 'the world's best sprinter is Johnson'. After the event, both Johnson and Bailey argued several times, and Bailey, who had been far removed from the public interest even though he had set a relatively new 100m record, raised such complaints in several interviews, and Johnson said to his hometown, 'In the world' They put up a large signboard that read, "Where the fastest man lives" and set the oil on fire. [12] Bailey's father, who saw the news, became very angry and put up a billboard saying 'Where the world's fastest man 100m winner Bailey lives', and a rather childish war of nerves continued. In the end, an idea came up to revive this nerve war as an event, and the result of an agreement between Johnson, who insisted on a 200m match, and Bailey, who insisted on a 100m match, was the 150m race. Before the showdown, they went on tour while maximizing the war of nerves between each other like a boxing match, and Johnson helped to attract attention by further emphasizing his unique character and golden spikes. However, the result was Bailey's victory as Johnson withdrew due to an injury after suffering a sudden muscle spasm halfway through. Thanks to his strong appearance and unique character, many experts and viewers predicted Johnson's dominance (or hoped for dominance), but viewers looked at him with dismay, and only a few enthusiastic Canadian fans and Bailey himself were happy. .

Softball , beach volleyball , and mountain biking were first played at this event.

Professional cyclists were allowed to participate starting from this event. The individual time trial, held for the first time in place of the previous team time trial, was won by five-time Tour de France winner Miguel Indurain of Spain. And the MTB cross-country men's and women's events were added to the official events from this event.

Women's soccer appeared for the first time.

Wrestling freestyle 100kg gold medalist Kurt Angle became a professional wrestler active in WWE and TNA through ECW after the Olympic gold medal .

Carl Lewis wins his fourth consecutive Olympic long jump title at the age of 35.

In women's archery , Korea's Kim Kyung -wook hit the camera lens in the middle of the target twice (the famous perfect gold) and won two gold medals.

The Argentina national football team, made up of Hernn Crespo and his friends, won the silver medal in men's football and Crespo himself was the top scorer. It was a strong team in its own way, although it was less powerful than in the 2004 Athens Olympics, when it was completely wiped out by itself like Carlos Tevez . The team that defeated Argentina and won the gold medal was the Nigerian national football team coached by Joe Bonfrere .

Katerina Serebrianska becomes the first Grand Slammer in rhythmic gymnastics to win gold

Tonga 's Paa Wolfgram won the silver medal in boxing super-heavyweight behind Ukraine 's Vladimir Klitschko , becoming the first Oceania country outside Australia and New Zealand to produce a medalist.

On the other hand, it was a nightmare for Britain, which had consistently performed well in the Olympics, and one gold medal from rowing was the only gold medal the UK won in this event. In the end, the tournament ended with a humiliating record of 1 gold medal, 8 silver medals, 6 bronze medals, and an overall 36th place.

Japan also had a very poor performance at the Olympics, winning only three gold medals in judo, but no gold medals in any other event. gave poor grades.

The last person to light the torch was legendary boxer Muhammad Ali . The scene in which he lit the torch while suffering from Parkinson's disease is one of the few touching scenes in this event.

It is also the first time since the division of North and South Korea that North Korea participated in the Olympics, flying artificial flags , in the mainland of the United States , which is known to them as a country of fierce enemies . [13] If North Korea had boycotted the event, Kye Soon-hee , the greatest star in North Korean sports history, would not have been born.

In addition, the African island nation of Comoros participated in the Olympics for the first time. It is also the last Olympics in which Hong Kong , which returned to China in 1997, participated as a British territory. [14] Coincidentally, in the last competition she participated in as British Hong Kong , she won the first gold medal in Hong Kong history (women's sailing), and as a result, she was able to raise the British Hong Kong flag and play Hong Kong's God Save the Queen at the same time for the first and last time on the Olympic podium. Awards Ceremony Video

The main stadium for the Olympics was immediately renovated as Turner Field as soon as the Olympics ended and was used as the home stadium of the Atlanta Braves for 20 years before the baseball team moved to Sun Trust Park and is currently used as the football stadium of Georgia State University under the name of Georgia State Stadium . [15]

7. korea

Korea dispatched 300 athletes, the largest team except for the 1988 Seoul Olympics held at home , and recorded 7 gold medals, 15 silver medals, and 5 bronze medals. It's a waste of a name Olympic season 1 . [16]

Men's gymnastics ' Yeo Hong -cheol was a strong candidate to win the vault event at the time , but ended up only taking the silver medal due to unstable landing at the last minute. [17] [18] , Lee Bong-ju of the track and field marathon succeeded in keeping Spain's Martin Peace, who was a strong candidate for the title, in check, but was ultimately pushed out by South Africa's Josiah Tugwani, who was an ambusher , and had to be content with a silver medal. [19] [20] In women's handball, there was a close match against Denmark that went to overtime, but the team ran out of stamina at the end and had to give up its dream of winning three games in a row. At least in wrestling , Shim Kwon -ho won the gold medal, and Professor Kim Young-jun, who was in charge of commentary for the wrestling broadcast on KBS at the time , rose to stardom again by leaving out the catchphrase "I have to give you pateru" in the old southwestern dialect at the competition, and Boryung Pharmaceutical's 'Gelfos' advertisement. also appeared in [21]

In particular, the baseball and basketball events were truly dark history events. Even considering that professional players were not allowed to participate in baseball at the time, not only did they lose to the strongest team in baseball, Cuba , but also to the United States , Japan , Taiwan , and others, and even suffered the humiliation of losing to European teams, such as Italy , where baseball was considered unheard of . [22] Unlike baseball, where they managed to get at least one win against the Netherlands, basketball was a nightmare of complete defeat. They even got to the point where they were called the nightmare team, comparing it to the overwhelming victory of the US national team, which was called the dream team at the time, which consisted of NBA star players . [23] [24] For reference, the South Korean national basketball team in Atlanta in 1996 is considered the best national team in history along with the 2002 Busan Asian Games team. In basketball, it was a competition that was marred by a drinking scandal involving some of the players, including Jae Huh. As a result, several players had to be disciplined by the basketball association. [25] [26] [27] [28]

In the men's judo 71kg final, the moment Kwak Dae-sung was awarded the silver medal by judging, he fell backwards and was so resentful. . Even though it was a different event, it was even more so in contrast to the appearance of a player from another country who won the bronze medal and went around the stadium and held a ceremony with joy as if he had the whole world. [29] [30]

In soccer , it won its first win in 48 years since beating Mexico 5:3 at the 1948 London Olympics against Ghana, but then drew with Mexico and was caught 1-2 by Italy, which was confirmed to be eliminated in the last game, and their first win in 48 years . They blew their chances of advancing to the quarterfinals.

8. Korean side relay

For the competition, the three terrestrial broadcasters ( KBS , MBC , SBS ) and the newly established Korea Sports TV a year ago formed a joint broadcast pool. Each broadcaster decided in advance which events it would be in charge of broadcasting, and for events where medals were confirmed, all three broadcasters aired the broadcasting commentary for that event identically. This method was unprecedented in the history of Olympic broadcasting. Source : That's why if you watch the broadcast of Kim Kyung- wook's gold medal match in women's archery released by KBS, you can hear the voice of MBC announcer Song In-deuk.

The specific broadcasting events by broadcaster were as follows.

Joint broadcasting is effective in preventing overheated competition, but on the other hand, it can have the negative effect of incorrect broadcasting content being transmitted simultaneously to all channels. This eventually exploded during the track and field broadcast. Even though the Canadian team won first place and the gold medal in the men's 400m relay, the broadcast commentary kept repeating that the United States won first place.

9. etc

For the first time in Olympic history, it was an event that actively accepted the 'informatization wave' that was progressing rapidly at the time. Visa International, one of the IOC partners, distributed 'Visa Cash', a card-type electronic money with an integrated IC chip, to be used instead of the previous money. In this way, a technology promotion group was created to create an 'intercast' method that combines the Internet and broadcasting, and NBC made half of the 175 minutes of relay broadcasting to be produced in the intercast method. IBM connected 80 minicomputers and 7,000 PCs to store/manage 11,000 individual players' records, careers, and anecdotes . ( # )

Changed as criticism continued.[9] It participated in this competition for the last time under the name of British Hong Kong, and was returned to China in 1997.[10] British Hong Kong[11] Even Usain Bolt, who created a sensation as the best monster of all time, had a general opinion that this record was difficult to break. Of course, Johnson's 200m record, which was supposed to take at least 30 years, was eventually broken by Bolt in 12 years...[12] If you divide the race record simply by the distance run, Johnson's record is obviously overwhelming than Bailey's, because m/s comes out faster at 200m. Therefore, the American media and Johnson's aides also used it as a basis for asserting that Johnson was the fastest person in the world.[13] He did not participate in the 1984 Los Angeles Summer Olympics held in the same country. Afterwards, he did not participate in the 2002 Salt Lake City Winter Olympics .[14] Starting with the 2000 Sydney Olympics, it will participate as a special administrative region of China .[15] Home of the Georgia State Panthers[16] Season 2 is the 2004 Athens Olympics .
